pilot <- here::here(
  "data",
  "processed_pilot.csv"
) %>% 
  read_csv() %>% 
  mutate(
    song = gsub(
      "audio/",
      "",
      stimulus_song
    )
  ) %>% 
  rename(
    target = target_song
  )

In this study we sampled 30 participants, with each participant listening to 42 1 second exceprts. Participants rated each song in terms of the emotion they thought it expressed, its valence, and its arousal.

All song consdidered

correct_overall <- pilot %>% 
  group_by(target) %>% 
  summarise(correct = sum(correct)/n(),
            valence = mean(valence),
            arousal = mean(arousal))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
correct_overall %>% 
  arrange(target) %>% 
  knitr::kable(format = "html") %>% 
  kableExtra::kable_styling() %>% 
  kableExtra::scroll_box()

target <- pilot %>% 
  select(target, song) %>% 
  distinct(song, .keep_all = TRUE)

correct_songs <- pilot %>% 
  group_by(song) %>% 
  summarise(
    correct = sum(correct)/n(),
    valence = mean(valence),
    arousal = mean(arousal)
  ) %>% 
  left_join(
   target
  )  %>% 
  relocate(song, target)

      x = song,

    )

  ggtitle("All Songs")

Selecting Songs

We can see that the majority of songs are canidate songs. For the final experiment we need a pool of 16 songs. At the state of the experiment 4 sad and 4 happy songs will be randomly selected as cue songs and 4 happy and 4 sad will be randomly selected as target songs. To establish the pool I selected the middle 8 happy and sad songs

cut_bottom_sad <- correct_songs %>% 
  filter(
    target %in% c("sad")
  ) %>% 
  arrange(desc(correct)) %>% 
  head(12)

cut_top_sad <- cut_bottom_sad %>% 
  arrange(correct) %>% 
  head(8)

cut_bottom_happy <- correct_songs %>% 
  filter(
    target %in% c("happy")
  ) %>% 
  arrange(desc(correct)) %>% 
  head(12)

cut_top_happy <- cut_bottom_happy %>% 
  arrange(correct) %>% 
  head(8)

selected <- bind_rows(
  cut_top_sad,
  cut_top_happy
)

This has given us the selected songs
